  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Buyside liquidity refers to buy stop orders above swing highs; sellside liquidity refers to sell stop orders below swing lows. A swing high has a lower high on each side; swing low has a higher low on each side. Smart money targets these zones, sweeping them to trigger reversals or continuations.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify swing highs: a high with a lower high on each side; buyside liquidity sits above it.",
    "Identify swing lows: a low with a higher low on each side; sellside liquidity sits below it.",
    "Equal highs and equal lows also accumulate liquidity.",
    "Price touching or breaking a swing high/low completes a sweep: buyside sweep = price breaks above swing high; sellside sweep = price breaks below swing low.",
    "Distinguish liquidity grab from displacement: if price closes back inside the prior range after the wick, it's a grab; if it closes outside, it's displacement.",
    "On higher timeframes, identify major swing points for external liquidity; then drop to lower timeframe (e.g., 1-min) for precise entry.",
    "After a sweep, look for market structure shift (MSS) and displacement as confirmation.",
    "Update liquidity levels as new swing points form; old levels may become invalid.",
    "A liquidity grab lacks large aggressive candles and fails to sustain beyond the structure; often followed by a move to opposite side liquidity."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Price moves in a cycle: external liquidity → internal liquidity (FVG) → external liquidity. After a sweep, trade in the opposite direction: after buyside sweep, look for shorts; after sellside sweep, look for longs. Confirm with Order Block, Fair Value Gap, and MSS. Use higher timeframe liquidity as target and lower timeframe for entry. Avoid chasing false breakouts; anticipate reversals after a grab.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing buyside and sellside liquidity positions.",
    "Mistaking random highs/lows for liquidity without proper swing structure.",
    "Entering before liquidity is fully swept, getting stopped by false breakouts.",
    "Trading solely on liquidity sweep without Order Block, displacement, or MSS confirmation.",
    "Treating any touch of a high/low as a valid sweep; ignoring close location (inside vs outside range).",
    "Ignoring dynamic nature of liquidity; failing to update levels as new swings form.",
    "Over-relying on a single liquidity level without multi-timeframe and multi-layer confirmation.",
    "Assuming all stops are at swing extremes; neglecting equal highs/lows.",
    "Confusing external liquidity (swing points) with internal liquidity (FVG).",
    "After identifying a sweep on higher timeframe, not dropping to lower timeframe for entry.",
    "Mistaking a liquidity grab for a genuine market structure shift and entering in breakout direction."
  ],
